<DOC><DOCNO> AP890802-0294 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 2144EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Earns-RJR     08-02 0265</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Earns-RJR,0277</SECOND><HEAD>RJR Holdings Posts Loss in 2nd Qtr, Operating Income Up</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   RJR Holdings Corp., which acquired RJR NabiscoInc. for a record $24.5 billion in April, said Wednesday it lost$309 million in the second quarter because of costs associated withthe buyout.   But the company, which is 92.3 percent owned by the buyout firmKohlberg Kravis Roberts andamp; Co., said strong performances by its foodand tobacco businesses helped boost its operating income by 24percent.   ``We are pleased with the progress we have made in meeting ourobjectives for reducing debt,'' said Louis V. Gerstner Jr.,chairman and chief executive.   The company has reached agreements to sell about $2.6 billion inassets, mostly from the sale of five European food companies,toward its goal of $5.5 billion in asset sales.   ``At the same time, our core businesses are exceedingexpectations for earnings and cash flow,'' Gerstner said.   The loss for the three months ended June 30 compared with aprofit of $354 million, or $1.50 a share, at RJR Nabisco a yearearlier.   Second-quarter revenue rose 4 percent to $3.91 billion from$3.75 billion.   But operating income before amortization charges rose to $848million from $683 million a year earlier. Operatings income fromtobacco rose 16 percent while it was up 40 percent from foodoperations.   For the first six months, the new company lost $518 million incontrast to a profit of $627 million, or $2.59 a share, a yearearlier at RJR Nabisco.   Six-month revenue rose to $7.44 billion from $7.04 billion ayear earlier.</TEXT></DOC>